App Description:
This free Māui Dolphin app makes it easy for boaties, surfers and beach goers to report sightings of the world’s smallest and rarest marine dolphin on the West Coast of New Zealand.
 
WWF-New Zealand and Alphero teamed up to deliver this beautiful, interactive guide. It helps users identify a Māui dolphin and understand more about this iconic species, while making it easier to report a sighting so that information on their habitat can be collected, and their habitat protected.
 
Every sighting is valuable to help build a picture of where the dolphins are found and better understand their behaviour.
 
This information is collected by WWF, and the report is verified by an independent dolphin expert. WWF shares the data with the Department of Conservation (DOC), government and scientists to advocate for full protection for Māui dolphins throughout their entire range.

App Description: A multimedia journey through the history of Jubilees. The app originated as a tool guiding visitors through the exhibition "Antiquorum Habet", housed in the Senate of the Republic in Rome, in the wonderful setting of the Sala Zuccari in Palazzo Giustiniani on the occasion of the Jubilee of Mercy announced by Pope Francis. The exhibition includes documents and publications relating to the most significant moments of jubilee celebrations, including pilgrims' journeys and the history of the four Papal Basilicas: old and modern manuscripts and printed books, engravings, newspapers and magazines, photographs from Senate book and document collections, plus material borrowed from the Vatican Library, the Museum of the National Mint and Printing Institute, and the Vatican Philatelic and Numismatic Office. 1,400 pictures from over 600 sources are on display, with detailed information and fact-sheets, arranged in a variety of itineraries. The app also gives access to a wealth of documents that, owing to space limitations, could not make it to the physical exhibition.
